{"title_page": "Mark Kerr, 1st Earl of Lothian", "text_new": "{{Short description|Scottish nobleman and politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n'''Mark Kerr''' (or '''Ker'''), '''1st Earl of Lothian''' (1553{{snd}}8 April 1609) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] nobleman and politician. He became the first [[Marquess of Lothian|Earl of Lothian]] in 1606.<ref name=\"Lothian Except\"/><ref name=\"Peerage and Bartontegae\">{{cite web|title=Burke's Genealogical and Heraldic History of Peerage, Baronetage and Knightage|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RVggAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1254&lpg=PA1254&dq=1st+Earl+of+Lothian+mark+kerr&source=bl&ots=2DcFXxs7qK&sig=ACfU3U1jB7qCR7A7IaP9kodG3keZUsQOIg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8ypv1haTiAhUbIjQIHWb3B6wQ6AEwKXoECC4QAQ#v=onepage&q=1st%20Earl%20of%20Lothian%20mark%20kerr&f=false|website=Google Books|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHe was a member of the \"famous border family\" of Ker of Cessford.<ref name=\"Border Vol17\">Hugh Chisholm, {{cite web|title=The Encyclopaedia Britannica: A Dictionary of Arts, Sciences ..., Volume 17|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N1YEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=1st+Earl+of+Lothian+mark+kerr&source=bl&ots=W6tjbkhqgH&sig=ACfU3U0Ww-XAoXMkuVLa31QcGd71NlB-iA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8ypv1haTiAhUbIjQIHWb3B6wQ6AEwK3oECC8QAQ#v=onepage&q=1st%20Earl%20of%20Lothian%20mark%20kerr&f=false|website=Google Books|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref>  He was the son of [[Mark Kerr (abbot)|Mark Kerr]], abbot of [[Newbattle Abbey]], [[Midlothian]], and Helen Leslie, sister of the [[Andrew Leslie, 5th Earl of Rothes|Earl of Rothes]].<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/> The House of Kerr was of Anglo-Norman lineage, and the Kerrs of Fernihirst settled in Scotland in the 13th century.<ref name=\"Peerage 1606\">Edmund Lodge, {{cite web|title=Genealogy of the Existing British Peerage: With Sketches of the Family from 1840 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kY5AAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA304&lpg=PA304&dq=1st+Earl+of+Lothian+mark+kerr&source=bl&ots=zT7KUu7J_d&sig=ACfU3U1wIJwxSyT3AGxMRSvb3zBcd9_Z2w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiF1quLhqTiAhVCOH0KHckXALs4MhDoATAGegQIGBAB#v=onepage&q=1st%20Earl%20of%20Lothian%20mark%20kerr&f=false|website=Google Books|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref> Kerr and his family lived in Newbattle Abbey, a mansion occupying the site of a Cistercian abbey founded in 1140.<ref name=\"Lothian Except\">Colin McWilliam, Christopher Wilson, {{cite web|title=Lothian, Except Edinburgh, page 345|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=78tthJn_jaIC&pg=PA347&lpg=PA347&dq=1st+Earl+of+Lothian+mark+kerr&source=bl&ots=yWeGA08trm&sig=ACfU3U1ly5UGEuv7NfC4eyUUIltmWex09Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiF1quLhqTiAhVCOH0KHckXALs4MhDoATAEegQIGRAB#v=onepage&q=1st%20Earl%20of%20Lothian%20mark%20kerr&f=false|website=Google Books|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==His titles==\n\nKerr was named [[Vicar]] of [[Linton, Scottish Borders|Linton]] in 1567. He was appointed [[List of Masters of Requests#Masters of Requests (Scotland)|Master of Requests]] in 1577, a role he held until 1606. In 1581, he succeeded his father as Commendator of Newbottle.<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/> Like his father, Mark Kerr was an [[Extraordinary Lord of Session]] under king [[James VI and I|James VI]]<ref>{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Lothian, Earls and Marquesses of|volume=17|page=18}}</ref> beginning in 1584, with his lands in Newbottle made into a Barony.<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/>\n\nOn 28 October 1587, he was made a [[Lord of Parliament]] as Lord Newbottle, or possibly 15 October 1591.<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/> In 1587 he was made a baron and [[Privy Council of Scotland|Privy Counsellor]] in 1587, and in 1604 he. He acted as interim [[Lord Chancellor of Scotland]].\n\nHe was created Earl of Lothian on 10 July 1606,<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/> and resigned the office of Master of Requests in the same year.<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/>\n\n==Heirs and his death==\nHis wife Margaret was the daughter of John Maxwell, [[Lord Herries]]. Kerr and his wife were said to have 31 children.<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/> An English list of the Scottish nobility states his residences were \"Morphele\" and [[Prestongrange House|Prestongrange]]. His wife was a sister of [[Lord Herries]].<ref name=\"CSP 07011592\">{{cite web|title=Rogers, Charles, ''Estimate of the Scottish Nobility'', Grampian Club (1873), 71, (1 July 1592) also printed by PF Tytler, ''CSP Scotland'' etc., |url=https://archive.org/stream/estimateofscotti00gram#page/70/mode/2up|website=|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref> A daughter, Margaret, married [[James Hay, 7th Lord Hay of Yester]].\n\nHe died on 8 April 1609.<ref name=\"Complete1893\">George Edward Cokayne, {{cite web|title=Complete Peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, Extant, Extinct, Or Dormant, Volume 5 (1893), p.&nbsp;144-145|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wrIKAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA144&lpg=PA144|website=Google Books|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref> His wife was accused of causing his death through witchcraft.<ref name=\"Burke1254\">Bernard Burke, {{cite web|title=General and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire (1914), p.&nbsp;1254|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RVggAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1254|website=Google Books|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref> She died at [[Prestongrange House]] on 8 January 1617.<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/> \n\nHe was succeeded in his positions by his son Robert, 2nd Earl of Lothian.<ref name=\"Burke1254\"/> The second earl had no sons, and the title passed to his daughter Anne, as Countess of Lothian, and subsequently in 1631 her husband was created [[William Kerr, 1st Earl of Lothian]].<ref>''Correspondence of Sir Robert Kerr, first Earl of Ancram'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1875), pp. xlviii, li.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Marquess of Lothian]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Marquess of Lothian|Earl of Lothian]]\n  | years  = 1606&ndash;1609\n  | before = New creation\n  | after  = [[Robert Kerr, 2nd Earl of Lothian|Robert Kerr]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lothian, Mark Kerr, 1st Earl of}}\n[[Category:1553 births]]\n[[Category:1609 deaths]]\n[[Category:Earls of Lothian]]\n[[Category:Ordained peers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Scottish nobleman and politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n'''Mark Kerr''' (or '''Ker'''), '''1st Earl of Lothian''' (1553{{snd}}8 April 1609) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] nobleman and politician. He became the first [[Marquess of Lothian|Earl of Lothian]] in 1606.<ref name=\"Lothian Except\"/><ref name=\"Peerage and Bartontegae\">{{cite web|title=Burke's Genealogical and Heraldic History of Peerage, Baronetage and Knightage|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RVggAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1254&lpg=PA1254&dq=1st+Earl+of+Lothian+mark+kerr&source=bl&ots=2DcFXxs7qK&sig=ACfU3U1jB7qCR7A7IaP9kodG3keZUsQOIg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8ypv1haTiAhUbIjQIHWb3B6wQ6AEwKXoECC4QAQ#v=onepage&q=1st%20Earl%20of%20Lothian%20mark%20kerr&f=false|website=Google Books|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHe was a member of the \"famous border family\" of Ker of Cessford.<ref name=\"Border Vol17\">Hugh Chisholm, {{cite web|title=The Encyclopaedia Britannica: A Dictionary of Arts, Sciences ..., Volume 17|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N1YEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=1st+Earl+of+Lothian+mark+kerr&source=bl&ots=W6tjbkhqgH&sig=ACfU3U0Ww-XAoXMkuVLa31QcGd71NlB-iA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj8ypv1haTiAhUbIjQIHWb3B6wQ6AEwK3oECC8QAQ#v=onepage&q=1st%20Earl%20of%20Lothian%20mark%20kerr&f=false|website=Google Books|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref>  He was the son of [[Mark Kerr (abbot)|Mark Kerr]], abbot of [[Newbattle Abbey]], [[Midlothian]], and Helen Leslie, sister of the [[Andrew Leslie, 5th Earl of Rothes|Earl of Rothes]].<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/> The House of Kerr was of Anglo-Norman lineage, and the Kerrs of Fernihirst settled in Scotland in the 13th century.<ref name=\"Peerage 1606\">Edmund Lodge, {{cite web|title=Genealogy of the Existing British Peerage: With Sketches of the Family from 1840 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kY5AAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA304&lpg=PA304&dq=1st+Earl+of+Lothian+mark+kerr&source=bl&ots=zT7KUu7J_d&sig=ACfU3U1wIJwxSyT3AGxMRSvb3zBcd9_Z2w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiF1quLhqTiAhVCOH0KHckXALs4MhDoATAGegQIGBAB#v=onepage&q=1st%20Earl%20of%20Lothian%20mark%20kerr&f=false|website=Google Books|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref> Kerr and his family lived in Newbattle Abbey, a mansion occupying the site of a Cistercian abbey founded in 1140.<ref name=\"Lothian Except\">Colin McWilliam, Christopher Wilson, {{cite web|title=Lothian, Except Edinburgh, page 345|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=78tthJn_jaIC&pg=PA347&lpg=PA347&dq=1st+Earl+of+Lothian+mark+kerr&source=bl&ots=yWeGA08trm&sig=ACfU3U1ly5UGEuv7NfC4eyUUIltmWex09Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiF1quLhqTiAhVCOH0KHckXALs4MhDoATAEegQIGRAB#v=onepage&q=1st%20Earl%20of%20Lothian%20mark%20kerr&f=false|website=Google Books|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==His titles==\n\nKerr was named [[Vicar]] of [[Linton, Scottish Borders|Linton]] in 1567. He was appointed [[List of Masters of Requests#Masters of Requests (Scotland)|Master of Requests]] in 1577, a role he held until 1606. In 1581, he succeeded his father as Commendator of Newbottle.<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/> Like his father, Mark Kerr was an [[Extraordinary Lord of Session]] under king [[James VI and I|James VI]]<ref>{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Lothian, Earls and Marquesses of|volume=17|page=18}}</ref> beginning in 1584, with his lands in Newbottle made into a Barony.<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/>\n\nOn 28 October 1587, he was made a [[Lord of Parliament]] as Lord Newbottle, or possibly 15 October 1591.<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/> In 1587 he was made a baron and [[Privy Council of Scotland|Privy Counsellor]] in 1587, and in 1604 he. He acted as interim [[Lord Chancellor of Scotland]].\n\nHe was created Earl of Lothian on 10 July 1606,<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/> and resigned the office of Master of Requests in the same year.<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/>\n\n==Heirs and his death==\nHis wife Margaret was the daughter of John Maxwell, [[Lord Herries]]. Kerr and his wife were said to have 31 children.<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/> An English list of the Scottish nobility states his residences were \"Morphele\" and [[Prestongrange House|Prestongrange]]. His wife was a sister of [[Lord Herries]].<ref name=\"CSP 07011592\">{{cite web|title=Rogers, Charles, ''Estimate of the Scottish Nobility'', Grampian Club (1873), 71, (1 July 1592) also printed by PF Tytler, ''CSP Scotland'' etc., |url=https://archive.org/stream/estimateofscotti00gram#page/70/mode/2up|website=|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref> A daughter, Margaret, married [[James Hay, 7th Lord Hay of Yester]].\n\nHe died on 8 April 1609. His wife was accused of causing his death through witchcraft.<ref name=\"Burke1254\">Bernard Burke, {{cite web|title=General and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire (1914), p.&nbsp;1254|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RVggAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1254|website=Google Books|accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref> She died at [[Prestongrange House]] on 8 January 1617.<ref name=\"Complete1893\"/> \n\nHe was succeeded in his positions by his son Robert, 2nd Earl of Lothian.<ref name=\"Burke1254\"/> The second earl had no sons, and the title passed to his daughter Anne, as Countess of Lothian, and subsequently in 1631 her husband was created [[William Kerr, 1st Earl of Lothian]].<ref>''Correspondence of Sir Robert Kerr, first Earl of Ancram'', vol. 1 (Edinburgh, 1875), pp. xlviii, li.</ref>\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Marquess of Lothian]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Marquess of Lothian|Earl of Lothian]]\n  | years  = 1606&ndash;1609\n  | before = New creation\n  | after  = [[Robert Kerr, 2nd Earl of Lothian|Robert Kerr]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT